text: I think it has more to do with the diversion of socio-economic resources into political consumption up to a crisis (based on precedent).

In comparison to the West, plutocrats in China have less political security (a bad thing IMHO), but otherwise the general level at which capitalism is distorted by ulterior ('socialist') ideas is broadly comparable. Markets and private entrepreneurs make both places run. ...

... State management of businesses is more prominent in China (though highly delegated), but other types of political interference are far more extreme in the West. Chinese companies have exactly zero DEI shit to deal with, for example.
Perhaps if politicians could be trusted, but they can't.

... Both China of the West have horrible financial systems, ultimately based on variants of fascist macroeconomic fiat (government money printing). Cryptocurrencies are more tolerated in the West, which is a true liberal advantage, and could at some stage be decisive.

... Western media are freer, due entirely to Elon Musk. Since Western media are otherwise generally more dishonest than Chinese media, it would take only a modest political upset in the West to reverse its advantage here.
Not a bad thing if true IMHO. Securing a good emperor still an unsolved problem (but the Western version of the problem is also nowhere close to a solution).

... Chinese media controls take the form of a state epistemic ritual, which the public understands, and privately discounts. In the West, regime propaganda takes the form of wild hellfire preaching by communist lunatics, which the lashed public writhes and spasms to confusedly.
In the spirit of Elon Celebration Week, have to note that no one is talking about 'Woke Capitalism' anymore, and that's basically down to him.
... Yes, it's crazy that the entire western economic system could hurtle into puke-striped cringe until one autist said 'Do this instead', but it is what it is.

The critique of Woke Capital, based on derision memes and Rufo-type counter-activism, could only be successful when it was shown that businesses didn't have to be like this (and looked vastly cooler when they weren't).

... Two things:
1) Creating a (roughly) free speech environment on X, rather than a Woke Capital resonance chamber (Jack's Twitter), and 
2) (Still more importantly) Providing a model of contemporary based capital, with SpaceX most vividly. ...
... Since 'X' is 33 by alphanomics, and the 33rd prime is 137, we can confidently refer to what has happened here as 'Current-137 Capitalism'.
Exit in all dimensions.
How has X not?
You did more than anyone to make it widely risible, but the second crucial element is offering an alternative model for emulation, and only a based plutocrat could do that.
Tendentially less, though.
